# How to use this template

Copy to `docs/plans/YYMMDD_plan-name.md`. Fill the sections below. Delete this header block in the copy.

Rules:
- **No implementation details.** No file paths, no function signatures, no library calls in the plan body. Implementer discovers those at build time. Steps describe *what*, not *how*.
- **Plan body is immutable after work begins.** Do not edit Goal/Approach/Non-goals/References/Validation/Open Questions to match reality. Record divergence in Implementation Log instead.
- **Non-goals cap scope.** LLMs over-build. State explicitly what NOT to do — adjacent refactors to skip, abstractions not to introduce, files not to touch. Cheap to write, prevents drift.
- **References point, not prescribe.** List what's relevant; don't tell implementer what to do with each.
- **Validation is the implementer's self-check before declaring done.** High-level — user-visible behavior, manual checks, smoke tests. Not test names or assertions. If you can't satisfy Validation, you're not done.
- **Required sections must stay.** Goal, Approach, Non-goals, References, Validation, Open Questions, Implementation Log are required. Add other sections (Risks, Rollout, Dependencies, etc.) when they earn their place — but don't pad with empty ceremony.
- **Status starts as `draft`.** Promote to `active` when work begins, `completed` when done, `abandoned` if dropped.
- **Improve this template** if you hit friction using it.

---

```
---
status: draft
created: YYMMDD
updated: YYMMDD
# outcome: <one-line headline> — set on terminal status only (completed / abandoned). Single most-load-bearing fact for the next session; saves rereading the Impl Log to learn whether the plan worked.
---

# Plan Title

## Goal
One paragraph. Why this plan exists, what success looks like.

## Approach
High-level steps. What to do, not how.

## Non-goals
What NOT to do in this plan. Adjacent cleanup to skip, abstractions not to introduce, files/areas not to touch. Empty if truly none, but think before leaving empty.

## References
Files, dirs, or docs the implementer should know about. One line each:
`path/to/thing — why it matters`

## Validation
Implementer's self-check before declaring done. High-level — user-visible behavior, manual checks, smoke tests. Not specific test names. If you can't satisfy these, you're not done.

## Open Questions
Bullet list. Empty if none.

## Implementation Log
Append-only. Filled by implementer.
- Deviations from Approach and why
- Decisions made at build time that future readers need
- Concise insights — what worked, what surprised, what to avoid
```
